\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\cb3\highlight3 What Is Similar?}
\par\pard\plain \fi720\ltrch\loch \f1\fs24\b1\i0\ul\ulc0\cb3\highlight3
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 Like all artforms, not all computational art is concerned with narrative and character - a lot is though (videogames and interactive fiction most consistently). }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Ludologists disagree - both sides seeking a Platonic ideal. Eskelinen\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s ludicrous comparison to a ball \u8220\'93starts telling stories\u8221\'94 - nobody is saying that! - \u8220\'93 "mechanics and story can have an important role to play in a game" - Henry Jenkins\u8217\'92 \u8220\'93not-not-narrative\u8221\'94, Aarseth and Juul against games as stories - Frasca sees it as \u8220\'93simulation vs. Narrative\u8221\'94 (2003) - he says it is bunkum. Aarseth sees them as \u8220\'93machines or sign-generators\u8221\'94 - I agree, but that does not mean that we are not authoring stories, or that artists do not need to approach it as an exercise in storytelling.}
\par\pard\plain \fi720\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 In general, their aim vis-a-vis characters is no different from any other form of art - to create characters of quality, that have resonance - \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93arrogant\u8221\'94 to assume that other artforms aren\u8217\'92t concerned with the same things. Characters which the audience can imaginatively and emotionally connect with and augment themselves, how they }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93affect us, move us, impact us and make us reflect\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3  (Mullaney). This is not controversial that games do this. }
\par\pard\plain \fi720\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 Computational characters still fit our definition at the start. It is artificially partial (not a complete human being - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93an agent is just a set of sentences\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3  (Praxis article), and videogame characters are collections of assets operating in a system, a }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93set of silicon circuits and unfeeling connectors\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3  (Half-Life Bots) - pursuit of \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93strong AI\u8221\'94 is mostly discredited, making a human, nor is this important to what I am doing). Indeed, the extent or nature of their partiality may be the issue. }
\par\pard\plain \fi720\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 Still individual - with OOO, even more so than in stories because they are modular, rather than serial, or perhaps part of the system still - part of the artwork, but individually recognisable in the way we talked about in last chapter.Can\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92t necessarily separate the characters from the experience of the game itself - or should we? Must set up the whole experience. Like before, we are not trying to separate characters from their containing work - maybe just saying that they are not a single mode within a story - the story must be viewed from their perspective.}
\par\pard\plain \fi720\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 Still represented in a medium, }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93realises an environment\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3  (Laurel) not that interested in what the medium is - \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93sensation\u8221\'94 (perception) for LeBlanc (Costikyan) and \u8220\'93narrative\u8221\'94 - creating a representation - either physical, virtual or in between, like mine. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Presence in game world\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 - sometimes completely virtual, sometimes involves the real world.}
\par\pard\plain \fi720\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 It is perceived and processed by a \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91player\u8217\'92 or \u8216\'91user\u8217\'92, who is engaging in a }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93lusory attitude\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3  (Bernard Suits, other people who talk about this?), }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 expression\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 , }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93masochism\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  (reception contract), }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 a }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93fantasy\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3  (LeBlanc), an intentional stance. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 reader response applies. ". Gaming connects well with this theory because it is such an active event where meaning is creating within a certain contextt between the game and the gamer." - a 'transaction' (Sanders) - \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93discovery\u8221\'94 is a \u8220\'93game pleasure\u8221\'94 - HCI book \u8220\'93partnership\u8221\'94 with computer. - \u8220\'93generic user\u8221\'94, or \u8220\'93several specific users\u8221\'94 (HCI book) - or \u8220\'93personae\u8221\'94 - what terms in QA - \u8220\'93enjoyment\u8221\'94, \u8220\'93emotional response\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93stakeholder\u8221\'94 (a term for user\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93reader\u8221\'94, in textual theory}
\par\pard\plain \fi720\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3  It has its beginnings in a creative act (an authoring) - by a human designer, at some point (maybe not direct authoring, though) }
\par\pard\plain \fi720\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 They act and behave - indeed, they are \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91agents\u8217\'92 which still, by the same processes described in the last chapter, constitute a narrative, and thus games form narratives themselves (despite ludology (Juul) vs. Narratology debate, S+Z believe games tell narrative, Ryan sees games and literary texts as two different narrative modalities, Espen Aarseth saw them as post-narrative\u8221\'94 and Henry Jenkins \u8220\'93not-not-narrative\u8221\'94.}
\par\pard\plain \fi720\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 Their narratives, and characters, and the experience of them, as still perceived and judged by particular markers of quality - reviews, thinkpieces - key aim of game authors to create resonant characters. The audience\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s role in creating that character is still very important, an interplay of their imaginations and the unique potentials of the game itself. Lankoski\u8217\'92s \u8220\'93allegiance\u8221\'94, judgement and }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 (for lankovski) eliciting sympathy or antipathy based on this. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Recognition\u8221\'94, \u8220\'93alignment\u8221\'94}
\par\pard\plain \fi720\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 So computational art shares enough of the same qualities and aims as other narrative artforms to make studying computational character through similar filters worthwhile. But what makes them different, both from other artforms generally and artforms before it specifically? Are there fundamental differences that require a different approach, or certainly a modified approach? Not completely different, and not completely the same. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Though there is much to be learned form traditional narratives\u8230\'85 [not] understanding their fundamental differences, the discourse becomes ultimately irrelevant\u8221\'94.}
\par\pard\plain \fi720\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa240\sb240\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 How Different?}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa240\sb240\ltrch\loch \ls2\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Often talk about \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93unique\u8221\'94 potential - a break from previous media. Not necessarily unique (look at last section) but Brendan Keogh calls it \u8220\'93particular\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93maybe all media forms are immersive or interactive in one form or another, and video gams are just immersive and interactive in particular ways\u8221\'94 Manovich points out that the potentials of computational media have been seen elsewhere - but more prevalent now, and more focussed.}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa160\sb160\ltrch\loch \ls3\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Unlike old art, is not \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93hardwired\u8221\'94 (Manovich), but }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93variable\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 , }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93movement from object to signal\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  (Manovich) - is a living system that changes its outputs according to inputs. Not a fixed, diegetic structure. Narrative is not fixed, elements are not fixed; instead, a }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93framework\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 (Costikyan) a \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93space of possibility\u8221\'94, }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93the aesthetics of interactive systems\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 (S+Z) Still representational, but those representations (also called \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93embedded\u8221\'94), Forcier\u8217\'92s }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93static units\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  are dealt with \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91procedurally\u8217\'92, combined and processed as units of info in a system of info. \u8216\'91Runs\u8217\'92 according to \u8216\'91rules\u8217\'92, has \u8220\'93emergence\u8221\'94 (S+Z), }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93flexible and organic\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  (Zimmerman) - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93machines \~of \~inputs \~and \~outputs \~that \~are \~inhabited, manipulated, \~and \~explored.\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  (Zimmerman). \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Procedural\u8221\'94 (Bogost) and (Murray)}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\sa240\sb240\ltrch\loch \ls4\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Different for author - creating a system, a \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93rule-based formal system\u8221\'94 (Juul) - not telling one story - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93second-order design\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  (S+Z). Creating the \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91potential\u8217\'92 for narrative to take place through manipulation or observation of a system. The themes, the potential narratives. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Narrative systems\u8221\'94 - "the middle-space between interaction and immersion, where the produral meets the encyclopedic and the participatory meets the spatial, is where narrative resides." \u8220\'93}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 a game, as it is played, is a collaboration between the developers and the players, a journey of mutual discovery, a democratic artform in which the shape of the game is created by the artist, but the experience of the game is created by the player.\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94 - Costikyan - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 It's a dispenser of stories, customized to the individual who is playing at the moment.\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 Will Wright - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 overall the narrative is unique to each player and to each play\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 (Forcier). }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 "game designers create the rigid structures of rules from which play will emerge". "Traditional media are representational, not simulational."}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  - not entirely true, but mostly true. So, dealing with procedural simulations in which we have influence and can tell stories rather than merely be given them. - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 "video games are just a particular way of structuring simulation, just like narrative is a form of structuring representation." Has rules - "The key trait of simulational media is that it relies on rules: rules that can be manipulated, accepted, rejected, and even contested.\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8221\'94 - }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 "symbolic representation" Wexler - Modelling (Klugl and Bazzan) (rules) and simulation ("executing a model")}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\sa160\sb160\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 How is that narrative created, then? Interactivity - difficult term - through interface - all art is interactive, as the last chapter showed. Also not all interactive, but that interaction is important for the types of computational art that I am interested in. Different for use - usually (but not always, though I am interested mainly in those that are) involves the input and }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93explicit interaction\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  (S+Z), interacting with story (Klug) or }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93direct interaction\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 (Mullaney), }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93purposeful interaction\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3  (Costikyan)}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  of a \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91player\u8217\'92 or \u8216\'91user\u8217\'92 - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93to explore, to make determinations, to take decisive actions, and to follow our choices to their conclusions\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 . It is \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91operated\u8217\'92 (Bogost), not just experienced vicariously or spectated. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Player control\u8221\'94, \u8220\'93actions are meaningful\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 (Makai), }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93interactive decisions\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  (Koster). }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 much of their structure is invisible to the user\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 (Costikyan) - a snapshot on the system - their traversal of it constitutes their narrative - manual, instead of merely ideological or imaginary, interpretation. Have material agency - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93the satisfying power to take meaningful action and see the results of our decisions and choices\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 , }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 a level of }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93personal, physical involvement that is not possible in more traditional works of fiction.\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 in a world that may be fictional, but that my exercise of will can shape and alter, as though an I, somehow apart from me but feeding perceptions back to me, acts in that world.\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3  (Tavinor). }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 "new media move us from identification to action"}{\f1\fs24\b1\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 (Manovich). Provides feedback loops, }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93participatory\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  (Murray). This is what we mean by the \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93ergodic\u8221\'94 in games, even if it isn\u8217\'92t all like that (Newman) - \u8220\'93marriage contract\u8221\'94 between user and system (Wegner). Not all computational art needs to be interactive, but very important for most forms - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 "The evolution of computer technology from the 1970s to the 1990s is expressed by a paradigm shift from algorithms to interaction" }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 (Wegner) or rather a combination of the two. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 "free movement within a more rigid structure"}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  - I'll stick with that, what we often mean by \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91play\u8217\'92, but \u8216\'91play\u8217\'92, again, has difficult affordances - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93The simulated reality in the representation becomes procedural, and thus unpredictable, more closely imitating real life. And this procedurality makes it possible to add the most sought-after component of all: the spectator himself as an active element in the work of art.\u8221\'94  - }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Weiner (1948) - cybernetics, feedback loops, systems (similar to how we interpret books but two-sided) - creating arbitrary rules within systems - not eating meat in minecraft (5/10) as well as performing the designed interactions - interpreting those in different ways - "encouraged affective states" (Keogh) - "We have historically intellectualised videogames as hard configurative systems while downplaying the fact that the reason we really play a videogame is because it feels real good within our soft meaty body. Videogames are a carnal pleasure." \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93The field of human-computer interaction largely grew due to this change in interactive pace\u8221\'94 - from batch processing to richer interaction. \u8220\'93Communication between user and system\u8221\'94 (HCI book) - acting on feedback - \u8220\'93interactive cycle\u8221\'94. A system containing an interface. In recent years increased the \u8220\'93bandwidth of communication\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93goal-seeking behaviour\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93in a world of partial knowledge\u8221\'94 - \u8220\'93epistemological interaction\u8221\'94 (Tavinor, Costikyan) - videogames because \u8220\'93the visual channel is used as the predominant channel for communication\u8221\'94}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa240\sb240\ltrch\loch \ls3\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Relies on the capabilities of the modern, digital computer, (Frasco) - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 "it is extremely difficult to model complex systems through cogwheels."}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 ) part of the }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93new media revolution\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  (Manovich) (Bogost - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93cheaper, faster,}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 more capacious, and more connected\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8221\'94)}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  in all its multivariant forms - to compute, to calculate, operate using algorithms and other data manipulation, to manipulate (Weiz - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93symbol manipulator\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 ) to store data (}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8221\'94encyclopedic\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  Murray), to represent everything as numbers which can be manipulated), algorithms, to represent, to sense, }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93network remote locations, manipulate large amounts of information, automate complex processes, and provide very immediate feedback\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  (Zimmerman). Interacting with information/data through \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93a new cultural metalanguage, the interface\u8221\'94 - not sure it is new, but certainly particular.}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\sa160\sb160\ltrch\loch \ls4\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Not necessarily a \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93unique\u8221\'94 potential, as we like to posit (I must be able to find hundreds of references for this assertion - "Traditional storytelling normally deals with endings in a binary way." - completely disagree). \u8220\'93}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 videogames so often insist separate them from the stodgy changelessness of novels, films, even the plastic arts.\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94 (Bogost) - }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Remember, other kinds of art use computation, use interactivity, use \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93scripting\u8221\'94 all these things that we are concerned with - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93While \~every \~poem \~or \~every \~song \~is \~certainly \~a \~system, games \~are \~dynamic \~systems \~in \~a \~much \~more \~literal sense.\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  (Zimmerman) but using modern computer technology allows us to use them at a scale and complexity and a relevance to a wide audience which is certainly unprecedented and which changes the experience (NWF - new media does things that previous media did, but quicker, in parallel, and }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93at time of audience experience\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93A focus on a new type of storytelling\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 (Leibowitz and Klug, 2012) . Not all attempt to reach this potential, but I would argue that all are interested in it to some degree - and really we are interested in those that pursue this potential. }
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa160\sb160\ltrch\loch \ls4\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Also cannot be called the \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91best\u8217\'92 or an \u8216\'91advance\u8217\'92 on any other form (again, as many people tend to talk about it) - but they are different, with their }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93own narrative language"}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 (Ryan), }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 and of course their specific methods, techniques and technologies, many of which I have used in my own work. Old ideas combined with new technologies - NWF - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 "a blossoming of new models of character, story and language". - }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 and requiring new ways of thinking about the act of authoring, of making art - and of making characters.}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3  }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 "we want new media narratives, and we want these narratives to be different from the narratives we have seen or read before.\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Tavinor talks about the number of emotions you can feel increasing (guilt, remorse, pride, ashamed, jealous }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 (Brock, 2007}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 ). }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 "perhaps there are ways that only games can signify"}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3  (Zimmerman) - LeBlancs }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93taxonomy of game pleasures\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 (Costikyan) - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93fellowship\u8221\'94 -}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Goal-oriented/participatory affects are unique to games - in films, it is "affective mimicry and simulation of the characters". Rogers, Carpentier and Barnard - interactive media enjoyment comes from degree of control/interactivity/agency.}
