\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\sa160\sb160\ltrch\loch \ls5\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 For those videogames that are interested in narrative (remember Currie and others from first chapter) characters are very important to such examples of computational art. Their deeds constitute a narrative - and when we are looking at procedural, interactive art, those deeds are controlled and plotted in real-time by the computational and materially interactive power of the computer - meaning that characters, their deeds and the audience\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s interactions with them are central to narrative computational art. \u8220\'93Centrality of the AI character to gameplay\u8221\'94, and Ermi and Mayra (2003) and Mallon (2007). }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 It is, technically, what Klugl and Bazzan call "agent-based modelling" - "decision makers" - certain bots - "computer program designed to operate autonomously, performing scheduled, responsive, or real-time operations in a computer, through the Internet, and/or on social media networks. What distinguishes bots from other kinds of software is that they interact with and/or produce content for humans, often assuming a human persona."}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa160\sb160\ltrch\loch \ls6\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 Caveats - Will be mainly looking at videogame characters as examples of computational artistic characters, but my methodology also takes into account other examples and disciplines which share many of these methodological challenges (see my bibliography). I do not mean to just privilege videogames characters, but it is my research background and focus, and while I may not call Project knole a \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93game\u8221\'94, this does not mean that it does not share most of its attributes with videogames - it just means that the term \u8220\'93game\u8221\'94 is a troublesome one, no matter what it is attached to. }
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 Also focussing on NPCs - characters in the gameworld, }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93intelligent agents\u8221\'94, \u8220\'93autonomous agents\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3  }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93embodied conversational agents\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3  . Project knole is not about the player controlling a character - it is about them directly interacting with the masterbeast - what we would call a non-player character. Of course, will see that this is a difficult distinction in my method - talk about the player perhaps choosing to identify with the character that Anne describes at the beginning of the }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 Housekeeping}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 , but do not have to - not prescriptive, the role is very bare, can decide for themselves (pathos) whether or not the creature has been left since the 18th century, and the actions of other players confuses it too - are they people who have received the pamphlet as well, due to the printer\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s deceit? - though also not interested in characters and other people, as in multiplayer (}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf4\cb3\highlight3 cite?}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 ) or \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91bots\u8217\'92 (Believable bots, other bot papers) - but the focus are on the \u8220\'93other\u8221\'94 characters. Of course, lots of game character scholarship is about the PC (Lankoski 2011, Lange, Theatre & Games chap, Tanenbaum & Bizzochi) - }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Player-character bond is often seen as one of the most important aspects of game storytelling.\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 This is an issue which is not vital to my work, and introduces concepts which are distinct from an audience\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s experience, interaction, judgement and evaluation of NPCs - such as \u8220\'93vehicular embodiment\u8221\'94 (Newman) - though many of the concepts talked about below have been written about in terms of NPCs, and are the ones which I have deemed to be applicable to NPCs as well - we still \u8216\'91control\u8217\'92 NPCs through our interactions, though it may be indirect. (}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf4\cb3\highlight3 cite?}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 ). }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 "conceptually problematic"}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  to focus on the PC. Tension between personality and control.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 So, }{\f1\fs24\b1\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 what is the potential of computational character?}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  In general, same as any other character - to be \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91resonant\u8217\'92. As said before, in general this means positive judgement, within the percepts of the medium, by an audience, and achieved by a combination (and in between) the representation itself and the imaginative extrapolation of the audience. This is no different for a game character, though the nature of that combination, and the representation, and what it does to the imagination, is different (or \u8220\'93particular\u8221\'94, remember) from other types of narrative artforms. Wexler points out games like Pong saw the actual rise of procedural and computational character, rather than merely represented computationally, like a digital photograph.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Computational characters have the potential to achieve their resonance through being computational. Not to be static artefacts, but to be part of a real-time computation, to change and adapt according to the rules of the system and the inputs of the player and other factors - to not have their stories told, but for their actions to depend on many factors decided at run-time. To have \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91agency\u8217\'92, and to be \u8216\'91agents\u8217\'92, \u8220\'93autonomous\u8221\'94 - just like the player, to }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93support the interactive experience of playing the game\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Of course, many game characters are not, explicitly, computational or procedural in any major way, even if part of something computed - (}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf4\cb3\highlight3 examples}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 ) - use the static techniques of other media, or restrict their computability (because of challenges, as seen in next section) - there is nothing wrong with this, nor do I see a truly \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93computational\u8221\'94 character as intrinsically better - but this potential is one that is intrinsic to the media and techniques used, and has a }{\f1\fs24\b1\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 promise}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  of a fundamentally different experience of fictional beings.}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa160\sb160\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f1\fs24\b1\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f1\fs24\b1\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 What is unique promise? }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Engaging narratives with life-like characters\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93INTERESTING PEOPLE\u8230\'85 IN INTERESTING PLACES\u8230\'85 DOING INTERESTING THINGS\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 , }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93improved realism\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  (Harris & Gittens 2015) }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 a \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93hypothetical future [in which] players could interact with computerized characters as round as those in novels or films, making choices that would influence an ever-evolving plot."}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  (Bogost) - return to his cynicism later.}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3  }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93more specific and interesting personalities", form \u8220\'93significant relationships\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 (Ueda)}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3  }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 (significant in \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91magic circle\u8217\'92, or outside it) and thus provide the agency for \u8220\'93strong narrative interactive experiences\u8221\'94 (Elizabeth talk). The interactivity of character (Sanocki), to intervene (Life Is Strange lady). }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 "creating relationships between the players and the characters in the game", "compelling, memorable characters". }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Players of modern video games increasingly expect Artificial Intelligence that is dynamic, is able to react to unexpected events, and behaves believably" \u8220\'93dynamic and unpredictable\u8221\'94.}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\sa160\sb160\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Measures of this promise: }{\f1\fs24\b1\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 believability. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Loyall provided best definition. Togelius talks about it as well.}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3  \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Life-like in appearance and behaviour, with a clearly defined personality and distinct emotional state, is driven by internal goals and beliefs, consistent in its behaviour, is capable of interacting with its environment and other participants, is aware of its surroundings and capable of changing its behaviour over time.\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Not necessarily }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93realistic\u8221\'94 (Mateas) but \u8220\'93socially situated, and able to reason in social terms\u8221\'94 }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 (Bailey) - - "convincingness and trustworthiness" - fogg and tseng, bartneck in Weiss and Tscheliegi - Reidl & Stern 2006 - more like real people, }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93more humanlike\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  (Johansson and Verhagen) in that they are materially simulated, mimetic, less diegetic. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94illusion of life\u8221\'94 (look at all the other models as well) To have }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93self-awareness, intentional states and self-impelled actions, to express emotions, the ability to use natural language and persistent traits\u8221\'94, }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 reactivity, interactivity, - \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93manifest believable behaviour\u8221\'94 - "plausible, malleable and loveable" - Evans - \u8220\'93}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Autonomy\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  not very different from most characters, but now has to be part of a system - all possible states that that character must be in - less control, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91second-order design\u8217\'92 and now is responsive to unpredictable or systemic input, which must be wide to be realistic. "Reciprocity" - Gouldner (in W&T) saying that this is "a pattern of social exchange" - not parasocial anymore. A move from parasocial to social relationships. Believability creates \u8220\'93engagement\u8221\'94 }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93emotion, personality, self-motivation\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  (Lankovski)., also providing a }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93possibility for a deeper interaction between players and NPC\u8221\'94, \u8220\'93co-presence\u8221\'94 (Bevalacqua) }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Bevacqua et al - "coupling" in virtual agents - the continuous mutual affect between two individuals - believability, co-presence ("being-with") and engagement - \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Interactivity also helps them form, a close bond wit hthe characters much more easily than in print or film\u8221\'94 - is this borne out by research?}{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cf1\cb3\highlight3  }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 Is it a unique potential, or just the same goals but particular to this media? }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 As Bogdanovych points out, belivability comes from non-interactive animation. So interactivity is important, but really it is computation - the real-time procedure of demonstrating a character, more like a real person - that is important.}
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa160\sb160\ltrch\loch \ls6\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3  Approaches - will discuss some, but AI \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93holds the most promise of change\u8221\'94 (Castronova), but is a holistic part of game design, as characters are tied to game system in many ways. Lankski and Bjork (2007) - "character design related to gameplay" - also mechanics in general, (nucle.ai\u8217\'92s point that AI is everything in game, dispersed model), \u8220\'93game feel\u8221\'94 (swink) - sound design, visual design, a holistic process. }
\par\pard\plain \tx240\tx720\li720\fi-720\sa160\sb160\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3	\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u9679\'3F	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 End with an example of a \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91good\u8217\'92 game character. Elizabeth? Came highest in \u8220\'93embodied conversational agent\u8221\'94. This is what I want for my character - to be dynamic, computational, and for that to lead to resonance - an artistic quality inherent, and not in spite of or in the absence of, the affordances of the medium that I choose to work in. To explore the potential of the medium, not to shrink from it. Characters in games are inextricable from the wider potential of games. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93We\u8217\'92re just scratching the surface of what games are and what they can be\u8221\'94}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3  (Alderman). Moving on from Murray\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s \u8220\'93incunabular days\u8221\'94. }{\f2\fs24\b0\i1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Beyond\u8230\'85 compelling entertainment to attain the force and originality that we associate with art?\u8221\'94 - }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93we do not yet fully know what computational can do and do not yet fully understand the expressive capacities of [computational art]\u8221\'94Bartle - "If virtual worlds could be populated by intelligent NPCs, all manner of doors would open". }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cb3\highlight3 Do all characters need to be this \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8216\'91believable\u8217\'92? What about \u8216\'91bit\u8217\'92 characters? Well, to a lesser extent, but we aren\u8217\'92t really focussing on \u8216\'91bit\u8217\'92 characters. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1\cb3\highlight3 Point out that not all characters are trying to be believbale - I am focussing on those that are, or which need to be.}}